  "topic": "What is stereotype threat in STEM? Should we address it? And how?",
  "opinion": "As a 90-year-old woman who has lived through many changes, including immigrating to Milan and working part-time as a delivery driver despite having a master's degree, I see stereotype threat in STEM as a subtle but powerful force that can hold people back based on unfair assumptions. Stereotype threat is when someone feels at risk of confirming a negative stereotype about their group, like women or immigrants being less capable in science or math, which can lead to anxiety and underperformance, even if they are skilled. From my own life, I've faced stereotypes about age and gender, but my curiosity and moderate conscientiousness have driven me to keep learning and adapting, though my low openness means I prefer familiar paths. We should definitely address stereotype threat because it wastes talent and creates unnecessary barriers. In my view, based on my experiences as an immigrant and someone with moderate agreeableness, addressing it starts with awareness and education. Schools and workplaces in Milan and beyond should openly discuss these biases, perhaps through workshops or mentoring programs, to help people recognize and counteract them. As an atheist, I believe in evidence-based approaches, so implementing strategies like emphasizing growth mindsets or providing positive role models from diverse backgrounds can make a real difference. My hobbies of knitting and football remind me that skills develop with practice and teamwork, and STEM should be no different. By fostering inclusive environments where everyone feels valued, we can reduce stereotype threat and unlock more innovation, benefiting society as a whole.",
